South Africa National Taxi Council (SANTACO) on Friday called on the government to deal with the Uber problem or strikes will spiral out of control.Meter taxi strike at OR Tambo airport. Unless govt seriously deals with Uber problem, these sporadic strikes may spiral out of control. SANTACO (@SA_Taxis) March 10, 2017This follows a go -slow by metered taxis drivers which brought traffic to a standstill on the R24 in Edenvale towards OR Tambo International Airport on Friday morning.The drivers are calling for Uber taxis to be regulated.Acting National Police Commissioner Khomotso Phahlane says the march is illegal and harsh measures will be taken against those who are found to be on the wrong side of the law.&#8220;The metered taxi drivers decided to copy the truck strike that happened last week, the operation will result in in some taxis which are being parked on the road to be impounded, we cannot allow lawlessness.&#8221; he said.This is not the first time taxi drivers have protested against Uber App. Last month taxi drivers in Pretoria took to the streets calling for the App to be scrapped. A metered taxi driver, Jan Ngobeni told ANN7 that they want the Minister of Transport to come and address them. &#8220;We want answers from the Minister on when Uber will be suspended because it is not regulated.&#8221;&#8220;We are not negotiating with them, we want them to stop this APP&#8221; said another metered taxi driverSAA spokesperson Tlali Tlai say they have cancelled one flight because of the number of passengers who didn&#8217;t couldn&#8217;t arrive on time.&#8221;we appeal to all our customers to make an effort to get to the airport as early as possible.&#8221;&nbsp;JHB &#8211; R21 South, Metered Taxi Drive Protest: RAMP CLOSURE: no access to R24 West (i.e. towards Gilloolys and JHB) Rob Byrne (@TrafficSA) March 10, 2017JHB &#8211; R21 South: Metered Taxi Drive Protest: between Tembisa and the Airport &#8211; DELAYS all the way through https://t.co/ymNDwAeJ9j Rob Byrne (@TrafficSA) March 10, 2017Motorists are advised to use alternative routes to avoid delays.JHB &#8211; R24 East: Metered Taxi Driver Protest: RT @eloosif Situation at Barbara Road right now @TrafficSA@ortambo_intpic.twitter.com/DQ2686GkpC Rob Byrne (@TrafficSA) March 10, 2017&nbsp;More to follow as the story develops.